Examine this dataset and see how the data is structured, see function ‘str’

The contents of the metadata file (./data/tree_metadata.txt(https://raw.githubusercontent.com/dmcglinn/quant_methods/gh-pages/data/tree_metadata.txt)) is provided here:

The dataset includes tree abundances from a subset of a vegetation database of Great Smoky Mountains National Park (TN, NC).

  • plotID: unique code for each spatial unit (note some sampled more than once)
  • date: when species occurrence recorded
  • plotsize: size of quadrat in m2
  • spcode: unique 7-letter code for each species
  • species: species name
  • cover: local abundance measured as estimated horizontal cover (ie, relative area of shadow if sun is directly above) classes 1-10 are: 1=trace, 2=0-1%, 3=1-2%, 4=2-5%, 5=5-10%, 6=10-25%, 7=25-50%, 8=50-75%, 9=75-95%, 10=95-100%
  • utme: plot UTM Easting, zone 17 (NAD27 Datum)
  • utmn: plot UTM Northing, zone 17 (NAD27 Datum)
  • elev: elevation in meters from a digital elevation model (10 m res)
  • tci: topographic convergence index, or site “water potential”; measured as the upslope contributing area divided by the tangent of the slope angle (Beven and Kirkby 1979)
  • streamdist: distance of plot from the nearest permanent stream (meters)
  • disturb: plot disturbance history (from a Park report); CORPLOG=corporate logging; SETTLE=concentrated settlement, VIRGIN=“high in virgin attributes”, LT-SEL=light or selective logging
  • beers: transformed slope aspect (‘heat load index’); 0 is SW (hottest), 2 is NE (coolest)

Above shows a map of the regional and local location of the elevational transects included in the dataset (from Fridley 2009 (http://plantecology.syr.edu/fridley/Fridley2009_jamc.pdf)).

Specifically, I would like you to develop and compare models for species cover for a habitat generalist Acer rubrum

and a habitat specialist Abies fraseri

Because this dataset includes both continuous and discrete explanatory variables use the function Anova in the packages car as such

explore <- trees[c( which(trees$species == "Abies fraseri"), which(trees$species == "Acer rubrum")), ]
abies <- trees[which(trees$species == "Abies fraseri"), ]
acer <- trees[which(trees$species == "Acer rubrum"), ]
abies$disturb <- as.factor(abies$disturb) # treat disturbance as a factor

abies$disturb <- factor(abies$disturb, levels = c("VIRGIN", "CORPLOG", "LT-SEL", "SETTLE"))
# this reorders the disturbance factors so that when we run the 'summary' function,
# CORPLOG, LT-SEL, and SETTLE are each compared to VIRGIN (VIRGIN essentially
# becomes the null hypothesis.

plot(cover ~ elev, data = abies)

plot(cover ~ tci, data = abies)

plot(cover ~ streamdist, data = abies)

plot(cover ~ beers, data = abies)        # plot each variable independently to 

plot(cover ~ disturb, data = abies)      # look for signal in graphs

# to see a significant effect of elevation on cover, and another one by distance
# to the nearest stream, though I would expect the effect of elevation on cover 
# to be stronger. I expect no significant effect of beers or tci on cover.

# VIRGIN data that the difference may not be statistically significant.

This will estimate partial effect sizes, variance explained, and p-values for each explanatory variable included in the model.

Compare the p-values you observe using the function ‘Anova’ to those generated using ‘summary’. All p-values are the same for both Anova and summary except for that of the disturbance factor. Anova runs one test comparing all disturbance types at once, while summary compares each disturbance type to the VIRGIN group, which serves as the null hypothesis.

For each species address the following additional questions:

  • how well does the exploratory model appear to explain cover? Abies fraseri: the exploratory model indicates that elevation is the best variable to explain cover. Elevation was the only explanatory variable with a significant relationship to cover. The main reason that this model shows promise, however, is that the r-squared is fairly high, especially for data collected in the field rather than a controlled lab setting. However, the adjusted r-squred value is lower than the r-squared value by about 0.08, which means that some overfitting has occurred and this model would probably be a better model if it included fewer explanatory variables.

    Acer rubrum: the exploratory model for acer rubrum does not explain cover very well. While several explanatory variables were found to have a significant relationship with cover, the r-squared value was very low, meaning that the explanatory variables do not explain much of the variance in the cover data. On top of that, the adjusted r-squared is lower than the r-squared. Although it is only slightly lower, the r-squared value here is so low that even a small decrease might indicate overfitting.

  • which explanatory variables are the most important? the most important explanatory variable in each model appears to be elevation.

  • do model diagnostics indicate any problems with violations of OLS assumptions?

  1. You may have noticed that the variable cover is defined as positive integers between 1 and 10. and is therefore better treated as a discrete rather than continuous variable. Re-examine your solutions to the question above but from the perspective of a General Linear Model (GLM) with a Poisson error term (rather than a Gaussian one as in OLS). The Poisson distribution generates integers 0 to positive infinity so this may provide a good first approximation. Your new model calls will look as follows:

For assessing the degree of variation explained you can use a pseudo-R-squared statistic (note this is just one of many possible)

pseudo_r2 = function(glm_mod) {
                1 -  glm_mod$deviance / glm_mod$null.deviance
}

pseudo_r2(acer_poi)
## [1] 0.03997917
pseudo_r2(abies_poi)
## [1] 0.60931

Compare your qualatitive assessment of which variables were most important in each model. Does it appear that changing the error distribution changed the results much? In what ways?

Elevation was the most important variable in every model. Changing the error distribution did change the results slightly, but not in a meaningful way, in my opinion. Elevation was still the only variable with a significant relationship to cover in the Abies fraseri model, and the variable of significance in the Acer rubrum model were the same in the lm and glm models, though the p-values were slightly different. Using the pseudo r-squared value as justification, it appears that the glm models were better, but only by a little bit.

  1. Provide a plain English summary (i.e., no statistics) of what you have found and what conclusions we can take away from your analysis?

What we have found is that elevation appears to be the primary factor of value in predicting any effect on cover. For Abies fraseri, using elevation as a predictor of cover will produce fairly reliable results. However, using elevation as a predictor of cover for Acer rubrum will not provide very reliable results.

  1. (optional) Examine the behavior of the function ‘stepAIC()’ using the exploratory models developed above. This is a very simple and not very robust machine learning stepwise algorithm that uses AIC to select a best model. By default it does a backward selection routine.

I am still a bit shaky on interpreting AIC results. But, the basics of what I know are that lower AIC’s indicate better models. Each of the results here appears to confirm what I found in my lm and glm models earlier, in that elevation appears to be the most important variable in the model. The best model for Acer rubrum appears to be a glm model using elevation and tci as the explanatory variables, and the best model for Abies fraseri appears to be the same (a glm model with tci and elevation as the explanatory variables).

  1. (optional) Develop a model for the number of species in each site (i.e., unique plotID). This variable will also be discrete so the Poisson may be a good starting approximation. Side note: the Poisson distribution converges asymptotically on the Gaussian distribution as the mean of the distribution increases. Thus Poisson regression does not differ much from traditional OLS when means are large.
